Exampel for RESTTEMPLATE and WEBCLIENT

RESTTEMPLATE : RestTamplate is a synchronous (Blocking) HTTP client for consuming Rest API'S.
               if any request will send to the server it will wait until response come.And other thread will be in waiting state.


WEBCLIENT : Webclient is a asynchronous (non-blocking) reative Http client for consuming the Rest API's is introduce in spring 5.


  EXAMPLE :-

✅ Step 1: Add Dependency
<dependency>
    <groupId>org.springframework.boot</groupId>
    <artifactId>spring-boot-starter-webflux</artifactId>
</dependency>

✅ Step 2: Create WebClient Bean

@Configuration
public class WebClientConfig {

    @Bean
    public WebClient webClient() {
        return WebClient.builder()
                .baseUrl("https://jsonplaceholder.typicode.com")   // base url
                .build();
    }
}

✅ Step 3: Create DTO
@Data
@AllArgsConstructor
@NoArgsConstructor
public class Post {

    private Long userId;
    private Long id;
    private String title;
    private String body;
}
✅ Step 4: Create Service (CRUD Operations)
@Service
public class PostService {

    @Autowired
    private WebClient webClient;

    // 🔹 CREATE (POST)
    public Post createPost(Post post) {
        return webClient.post()
                .uri("/posts")
                .bodyValue(post)
                .retrieve()
                .bodyToMono(Post.class)
                .block();
    }

    // 🔹 READ (GET by id)
    public Post getPostById(Long id) {
        return webClient.get()
                .uri("/posts/{id}", id)
                .retrieve()
                .bodyToMono(Post.class)
                .block();
    }

    // 🔹 READ (GET all)
    public List<Post> getAllPosts() {
        return webClient.get()
                .uri("/posts")
                .retrieve()
                .bodyToFlux(Post.class)
                .collectList()
                .block();
    }

    // 🔹 UPDATE (PUT)
    public Post updatePost(Long id, Post post) {
        return webClient.put()
                .uri("/posts/{id}", id)
                .bodyValue(post)
                .retrieve()
                .bodyToMono(Post.class)
                .block();
    }

    // 🔹 DELETE
    public String deletePost(Long id) {
        webClient.delete()
                .uri("/posts/{id}", id)
                .retrieve()
                .bodyToMono(Void.class)
                .block();

        return "Deleted Successfully";
    }
}

🔥 Important Interview Point

You used:

bodyToMono() → Single object

bodyToFlux() → Multiple objects

.block() → Converts reactive to synchronous

If using full reactive app (WebFlux controller), then remove .block() and return Mono<Post> or Flux<Post>.



Good 🔥 let’s move to the next important real-world step:

✅ Handling Errors in WebClient (VERY Important for Interviews + Real Projects)

Right now your code works only when API returns 200 OK.

But what if:

API returns 404

API returns 500

API is down

Timeout happens

If you don’t handle this → your app will throw exception.

🔥 Proper Error Handling with onStatus()
@GetMapping("/getAllPost")
public Mono<List<Product>> getAllPost() {

    return webClient.get()
            .uri("objects")
            .retrieve()
            .onStatus(
                    status -> status.is4xxClientError(),
                    response -> Mono.error(new RuntimeException("Client Error!"))
            )
            .onStatus(
                    status -> status.is5xxServerError(),
                    response -> Mono.error(new RuntimeException("Server Error!"))
            )
            .bodyToFlux(Product.class)
            .collectList();
}
✅ Global Fallback Handling

You can also use:

.onErrorResume(ex -> {
    System.out.println("Error occurred: " + ex.getMessage());
    return Mono.just(Collections.emptyList());
})

This prevents application crash.

🚀 Next Level: Timeout Configuration

By default, WebClient (from Spring WebFlux) uses Netty.

Add timeout in config:

@Bean
public WebClient webClient() {
    return WebClient.builder()
            .baseUrl("https://api.restful-api.dev/")
            .build();
}

Or add request timeout per call:

.timeout(Duration.ofSeconds(5))
🎯 Interview Question They Ask

👉 How do you handle errors in WebClient?

Answer:

Using onStatus() for HTTP errors

Using onErrorResume() for fallback

Using timeout() for slow API

